content.thinking:
The log shows the new code IS running — it wrote the state file and used `-open` instead of `-execute`. But the user says no notification appeared. Let me check if the `-open` flag is somehow interfering with the notification appearing. Looking at the terminal-notifier source, `-open` is a URL or file path — maybe passing an `.app` bundle as `-open` causes issues.

Wait, looking at the source code of terminal-notifier more carefully:
```objc
if (defaults[@"open"]) {
    NSURL *url = [NSURL URLWithString:defaults[@"open"]];
    if ((url && url.scheme && url.host) || [url isFileURL]) {
        options[@"open"] = defaults[@"open"];
    }else{
        NSLog(@"'%@' is not a valid URI.", defaults[@"open"]);
        exit(1);
    }
}
```

The `-open` value is passed through `NSURL URLWithString:` and checked. A file path like `/Users/nbr/.local/bin/PiSpeakFocus.app` needs to be a valid file URL. `NSURL URLWithString:` with a bare path might not work — it needs `file://` prefix, or we need to use `[NSURL fileURLWithPath:]`.

Let me check: does `NSURL URLWithString:@"/Users/nbr/.local/bin/PiSpeakFocus.app"` return a valid URL with a scheme? Probably not — it would return nil because there's no scheme. And `[url isFileURL]` would return false because the URL string doesn't start with `file://`.

That's why the notification didn't appear — terminal-notifier exited with code 1 because the URL was invalid!

The fix: prefix the path with `file://`.

